citeinfo.title: Ozark Plateaus seepage flow-line dataset, southern Missouri and northern Arkansas, 1982-2006
Ozark Plateaus seepage run dataset, southern Missouri and northern Arkansas, 1982-2006

descript.abstract: This dataset was compiled to summarize discharge measurements from several published groundwater and surface-water studies in the Ozarks of southern Missouri and northern Arkansas. The discharge measurements were part of numerous USGS studies to assess interaction between streams and groundwater aquifers. A gaining stream is described as a surface-water stream that gains water from the groundwater aquifer and a losing stream is described as a surface-water stream that loses water to the groundwater aquifer. This product is intended to be used in surface-water and groundwater investigations assessing water quantity, quality, and availability. The product includes flow-line data digitized along National Hydrography Dataset (NHD) flow lines and between adjacent discharge measurements (that is, seepage flow-line reaches). The seepage flow-line reaches include a calculation to determine if discharge between the upstream and downstream measurement points is increasing (termed "Gain"), decreasing (termed "Lose"), or remaining neutral if the net change in discharge is not greater than the error (termed "Neutral"). Original seepage-run studies included estimates of discharge measurement error and some studies estimated error along the seepage flow-line reach; however, because of the variety of ways that error was calculated in the original studies and to create a consistent error estimation for the entire spatial dataset, error was assumed to be 10% of the largest discharge measurement along the seepage flow-line reach. Contribution of discharge from tributaries and springs that emerge before flowing into the stream was taken into account, such that the net change in discharge between the upstream and downstream measurement points was calculated as the downstream discharge minus the total discharge from the upstream measurement point and from tributaries/springs. This calculation quantifies the amount of groundwater flow entering the stream as diffuse or point discharge, presumably into the stream bed. The net change in discharge was additionally calculated as the downstream discharge minus the total discharge from both the upstream measurement point and from surface-water tributaries only. This calculation quantifies the amount of groundwater entering the stream as discrete springs adjacent to the stream and diffuse or point groundwater flow directly to the stream bed. A positive net change in discharge results in the seepage flow-line reach gaining discharge (that is, "Gain") and a negative net change in discharge results in the seepage flow-line reach losing discharge (that is, "Lose"). Designations of gaining, losing, or neutral streams may vary between this dataset and the original studies because of differences in how error was calculated and other interpretations made in the seepage-run studies. Users are encouraged to refer to the source reports for further details about data collection methods, results, and interpretations of stream-aquifer dynamics. This spatial dataset is meant to provide a digital compilation of seepage studies in the Ozarks and to create a consistent dataset across studies completed over 24 years.
descript.purpose: This dataset compiled 24 years of U.S. Geological Survey (USGS) seepage-run data from 15 studies covering southern Missouri and northern Arkansas in the Ozark Plateaus Physiographic Province (Ozarks). Previously these data were only available separately from the original USGS studies. The dataset can be used in surface-water and groundwater investigations assessing water quantity, quality, and availability in the Ozarks. The dataset can be combined with the "Ozark Plateaus seepage point dataset, southern Missouri and northern Arkansas, 1982-2006" to view point and line data of previously published USGS seepage-run studies. Seepage-run data were collected by measuring discharge at points along a stream, as well as at tributaries and springs contributing water to that stream. Any differences between the upstream and downstream discharge measurements (greater than the measurement error and taking tributaries/springs into account) were interpreted as gaining streams (if downstream discharge was greater than upstream discharge) or losing streams (if downstream discharge was less than upstream discharge). The discharge data were originally collected as part of numerous USGS surface-water and groundwater studies to quantify the amount of water gained or lost by streams to aquifers; in some cases the data were collected as part of larger studies, such as groundwater modeling or stream water-quality monitoring. The Ozarks are one of the major karst provinces in the United States and karst geology is characterized by fractures and solution-enlarged conduits in soluble bedrock that allow intimate interaction between surface water and groundwater resources. Therefore, quantifying the interaction between surface water and groundwater is important for a better understanding of water quality and quantity in karst landscapes. The seepage flow-line reaches are intended to be used with the “Ozark Plateaus seepage point dataset, southern Missouri and northern Arkansas, 1982-2006" because seepage-run studies include both point (that is, discharge measurements) and line (that is, stream flow lines between adjacent discharge points) data. Users are additionally encouraged to read the original reports (which can are referenced in the “source” attribute field) to fully understand the data collection methods, results, and interpretations of individual seepage-run studies.
descript.supplinf: This dataset will be used as part of a regional study of the Ozark Plateaus aquifer system, to better quantify the exchange between surface water and groundwater.

attracc.attraccr: USGS discharge measurements are rated as either "Excellent" (measured discharge is within 2% of actual discharge), "Good" (measured discharge is within 5% of actual discharge), "Fair" (measured discharge is within 8% of actual discharge), or "Poor" (measured discharge is greater than 8% of actual discharge) (http://help.waterdata.usgs.gov/codes-and-parameters/discharge-measurement-quality-code). The discharge measurement errors from the original studies were not included in this dataset, so users should reference the source publication (which can be found in the “source” attribute field) for discharge measurement error information. To create a consistent error estimation for this entire spatial dataset (thus allowing consistent interpretation of stream gains and losses across the dataset), error was assumed to be 10% of the largest discharge measurement along the seepage flow-line reach. Designations of gaining, losing, or neutral streams may vary between this dataset and the original studies because of differences in how error was calculated and other interpretations made in the seepage-run studies. Users are encouraged to refer to the source reports for further details about data collection methods, results, and interpretations of stream-aquifer dynamics. This spatial dataset is meant to provide a digital compilation of seepage studies in the Ozarks and to create a consistent dataset across studies completed over 24 years.

dataqual.logic: Multiple rounds of quality assurance and quality control checked for internal consistency in the dataset between the discharge measurement point data (found in the "Ozark Plateaus seepage point dataset, southern Missouri and northern Arkansas, 1982-2006") and the attribute table of the seepage flow-line data. Seepage flow-line reaches were checked for correctness against the discharge measurement points for (1) codes for the upstream (codeU) and downstream (codeD) nodes match the siteIDs for the discharge measurement points, (2) discharge values for the upstream (dischU) and downstream (dischD) nodes match the values for the discharge measurement points, (3) total discharge from surface-water tributaries and springs contributing flow to the seepage flow-line reach (Trib_Total) are correctly summed from the discharge measurement points, and (4) names of surface-water tributaries and springs contributing flow to the seepage flow-line reach (Trib_IDs and Trib_Names) match the siteID and stream/spring names from the discharge measurement point dataset. The fields for GW_Tribs, GW_TribIDs, GW_TribNam, SW_Tribs, SW_TribIDs, and SW_TribNam were similarly checked. The calculations for the net change in discharge along the seepage flow-line reach (NetQ_GW and NetQ_dif) and designation of Gain/Loss/Neutral for the seepage flow-line reach based on those calculations (GorL_GW and GorL_dif) were also checked for correctness. All fields were checked for inappropriate "Null" values.
dataqual.complete: Discharge data used to construct seepage flow-line reaches are from previously published USGS reports. Substantial effort was made to include all available published discharge data from seepage-run studies for streams in the Ozarks of southern Missouri and northern Arkansas, but some 0 cubic feet per second discharge data values may be missing. Users are advised to read the rest of the metadata record carefully for additional details and encouraged to read the original source reports.

procstep.procdesc: Discharge measurement data from published USGS reports were digitized (see metadata for "Ozark Plateaus seepage point data set, southern Missouri and northern Arkansas, 1982-2006"). The point data included: the date the original data were collected (date), the original study citation for the discharge data (source), the stream name for the discharge measurement given as either stream name or stream name plus description from the original study (Stream), the site identifier for the discharge measurement point, either from the original study or created as part of digitization process (siteID), the discharge value in cubic feet per second (discharge), and any additional information about the data that users should be aware of (notes).

Seepage flow-line reaches were digitized from NHD data (at a 1:100,000 resolution) between adjacent measurement points of discharge. From the discharge point data, the following fields were added to the seepage flow-line reaches: name of the stream along the seepage flow-line reach (Stream), discharge of the upstream (dischU) and downstream (dischD) points, siteID of the upstream (codeU) and downstream (codeD) points, original date of measurement collection (Date), and the original source of the data (Source). A ReachID was created for each seepage flow-line reach. Any surface-water tributaries and springs contributing flow to the seepage flow-line reach were added to the flow-line data, where the total discharge, siteIDs, and names of tributaries/springs from the discharge point data were represented by the Trib_Total, Trib_IDs, and Trib_Names fields, respectively. Additionally, surface-water tributaries and springs were accounted for separately. Any surface-water tributaries contributing flow to the seepage flow-line reach were added to the flow-line data, where the total surface-water tributary discharge, siteIDs, and names of surface-water tributaries from the discharge point data were represented by the SW_Tribs, SW_TribIDs, and SW_TribNames fields, respectively. Any springs contributing flow to the seepage flow-line reach were added to the flow-line data, where the total spring discharge, siteIDs, and names of springs from the discharge point data were represented by the GW_Tribs, GW_TribIDs, and GW_TribNames fields, respectively.

The maximum discharge between the upstream and downstream discharge measurement points was calculated, which was necessary for calculating discharge error. Error was calculated as 10% of the maximum discharge between the upstream and downstream discharge measurement points along the seepage flow-line reach. The calculation for this was: maxQ = max(dischU, dischD)

The net change in discharge was calculated along the seepage flow-line reach between the upstream and downstream discharge measurement points, such that the net change in discharge was equal to the downstream discharge minus the total discharge from the upstream measurement point and from surface-water tributaries. This calculation quantifies the amount of groundwater entering the stream as discrete springs and diffuse groundwater flow, presumably directly into the stream bed. The calculation for this was: NetQ_GW = dischD - SW_Tribs – dischU.

The absolute value of the net change in discharge was calculated, which was necessary for determining whether the change in discharge between the upstream and downstream points was greater than the measurement error. The calculation for this was: AbsNetQ_GW = abs(NetQ_GW)

A logic statement was used to determine whether the net change in discharge along the seepage flow-line reach was greater or less than/equal to the discharge measurement error, where "true" means that the absolute value of the net change in discharge is greater than the error and "false" means that the absolute value of the net change in discharge is less than or equal to the error. The logic for this calculation was: def GLcalc_GW(AbsNetQ_GW, Error): if AbsNetQ_GW > Error: return "true" else: return "false" GLcalc_GW(!AbsNetQ_GW!, !Error_perc!)

The qualitative change in discharge between the upstream and downstream measurement points was determined, where "Neutral" means that the net change in discharge was not greater than the error (that is, GLcalc_GW = false). If the net change in discharge was greater than the error (that is, GLcalc_GW = true), then "Gain" means there was a positive net change in discharge from upstream to downstream (that is, NetQ_GW > 0) and "Lose" means there was a negative net change in discharge from upstream to downstream (that is, NetQ_GW < 0). The logic for this calculation was: def GorL_GW(GLcalc_GW, NetQ_GW): if GLcalc_GW == “false”: return “Neutral” elif NetQ_GW > 0: return “Gain” else: return “Lose” GorL_GW(!GLcalc_GW!, !NetQ_GW!)

The net change in discharge was calculated along the seepage flow-line reach between the upstream and downstream discharge measurement points, such that the net change in discharge was equal to the downstream discharge minus the total discharge from the upstream measurement point , surface-water tributaries, and springs. This calculation quantifies the amount of groundwater entering the stream as diffuse groundwater flow directly to the stream bed. The calculation for this is: NetQ_dif = dischD - Trib_Total – dischU

The absolute value of the net change in discharge was calculated, which was necessary for determining whether the change in discharge between the upstream and downstream points was greater than the measurement error. The calculation for this was: AbsNetQ_dif = abs(NetQ_dif)

A logic statement was used to determine whether the net change in discharge along the seepage flow-line reach was greater or less than/equal to the discharge measurement error, where "true" means that the absolute value of the net change in discharge is greater than the error and "false" means that the absolute value of the net change in discharge is less than or equal to the error. The logic for this calculation was: def GLcalc_dif(AbsNetQ_dif, Error): if AbsNetQ_dif > Error: return "true" else: return "false" GLcalc_GW(!AbsNetQ_dif!, !Error_perc!)

The qualitative change in discharge between the upstream and downstream measurement points was determined, where "Neutral" means that the net change in discharge was not greater than the error (that is, GLcalc_dif = false). If the net change in discharge was greater than the error (that is, GLcalc_dif = true), then "Gain" means there was a positive net change in discharge from upstream to downstream (that is, NetQ_dif > 0) and "Lose" means there was a negative net change in discharge from upstream to downstream (that is, NetQ_dif < 0). The logic for this calculation was: def GorL_dif(GLcalc_dif, NetQ_dif): if GLcalc_dif == “false”: return “Neutral” elif NetQ_dif > 0: return “Gain” else: return “Lose” GorL_dif(!GLcalc_dif!, !NetQ_dif!)

The length of the stream reach was calculated from the ArcMap generated Shape_Length field, where the Shape_Length was in meters and the stream reach length was converted to miles. This calculation was: Stream_Length = Shape_Length / 1609.34

dataIdInfo.idPurp: This dataset compiled 24 years of U.S. Geological Survey (USGS) seepage-run data from 15 studies covering southern Missouri and northern Arkansas in the Ozark Plateaus Physiographic Province (Ozarks). Previously these data were only available separately from the original USGS studies. The dataset can be used in surface-water and groundwater investigations assessing water quantity, quality, and availability in the Ozarks. The dataset can be combined with the "Ozark Plateaus seepage point dataset, southern Missouri and northern Arkansas, 1982-2006" to view point and line data of previously published USGS seepage-run studies. Seepage-run data were collected by measuring discharge at points along a stream, as well as at tributaries and springs contributing water to that stream. Any differences between the upstream and downstream discharge measurements (greater than the measurement error and taking tributaries/springs into account) were interpreted as gaining streams (if downstream discharge was greater than upstream discharge) or losing streams (if downstream discharge was less than upstream discharge). The discharge data were originally collected as part of numerous USGS surface-water and groundwater studies to quantify the amount of water gained or lost by streams to aquifers; in some cases the data were collected as part of larger studies, such as groundwater modeling or stream water-quality monitoring. The Ozarks are one of the major karst provinces in the United States and karst geology is characterized by fractures and solution-enlarged conduits in soluble bedrock that allow intimate interaction between surface water and groundwater resources. Therefore, quantifying the interaction between surface water and groundwater is important for a better understanding of water quality and quantity in karst landscapes. The seepage flow-line reaches are intended to be used with the “Ozark Plateaus seepage point dataset, southern Missouri and northern Arkansas, 1982-2006" because seepage-run studies include both point (that is, discharge measurements) and line (that is, stream flow lines between adjacent discharge points) data. Users are additionally encouraged to read the original reports (which can are referenced in the “source” attribute field) to fully understand the data collection methods, results, and interpretations of individual seepage-run studies.
dataIdInfo.idAbs: This dataset was compiled to summarize discharge measurements from several published groundwater and surface-water studies in the Ozarks of southern Missouri and northern Arkansas. The discharge measurements were part of numerous USGS studies to assess interaction between streams and groundwater aquifers. A gaining stream is described as a surface-water stream that gains water from the groundwater aquifer and a losing stream is described as a surface-water stream that loses water to the groundwater aquifer. This product is intended to be used in surface-water and groundwater investigations assessing water quantity, quality, and availability. The product includes flow-line data digitized along National Hydrography Dataset (NHD) flow lines and between adjacent discharge measurements (that is, seepage flow-line reaches). The seepage flow-line reaches include a calculation to determine if discharge between the upstream and downstream measurement points is increasing (termed "Gain"), decreasing (termed "Lose"), or remaining neutral if the net change in discharge is not greater than the error (termed "Neutral"). Original seepage-run studies included estimates of discharge measurement error and some studies estimated error along the seepage flow-line reach; however, because of the variety of ways that error was calculated in the original studies and to create a consistent error estimation for the entire spatial dataset, error was assumed to be 10% of the largest discharge measurement along the seepage flow-line reach. Contribution of discharge from tributaries and springs that emerge before flowing into the stream was taken into account, such that the net change in discharge between the upstream and downstream measurement points was calculated as the downstream discharge minus the total discharge from the upstream measurement point and from tributaries/springs. This calculation quantifies the amount of groundwater flow entering the stream as diffuse or point discharge, presumably into the stream bed. The net change in discharge was additionally calculated as the downstream discharge minus the total discharge from both the upstream measurement point and from surface-water tributaries only. This calculation quantifies the amount of groundwater entering the stream as discrete springs adjacent to the stream and diffuse or point groundwater flow directly to the stream bed. A positive net change in discharge results in the seepage flow-line reach gaining discharge (that is, "Gain") and a negative net change in discharge results in the seepage flow-line reach losing discharge (that is, "Lose"). Designations of gaining, losing, or neutral streams may vary between this dataset and the original studies because of differences in how error was calculated and other interpretations made in the seepage-run studies. Users are encouraged to refer to the source reports for further details about data collection methods, results, and interpretations of stream-aquifer dynamics. This spatial dataset is meant to provide a digital compilation of seepage studies in the Ozarks and to create a consistent dataset across studies completed over 24 years.
